<paragraph blockId="9.[136,1452,1450,1685]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,426,1589,1616]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Taxonomic notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boissier" authorityYear="1860" box="[426,715,1589,1615]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="peperomioides">
<emphasis box="[426,715,1589,1615]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Euphorbia peperomioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other prostrate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[1060,1180,1589,1615]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1060,1180,1589,1615]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Euphorbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1340,1452,1589,1616]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
by having leaves with symmetric base, lateral, glanduliform stipules and cyathial glands without petaloid appendages, sometimes with irregular margins that looks like horns.
</paragraph>
